	<div class="col-sm-8 index-section">
		<ul class="lists lists-linklist">
			<li>
				<a href="#FAQ-q1" class="js-collapsible">Do we have to use the GUI source code?</a>
				<div id="FAQ-q1" class="collapsible-body text-muted" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1">
					<div class="top-margin1-xs">
						No you do not have to use the GUI source code. If you would prefer to build from scratch using wireframes and visual designs that is your
						decision. As long as your final output looks and functions in the same way.
					</div>
				</div>
			</li>
			<li>
				<a href="#FAQ-q2" class="js-collapsible">What browsers does this GUI support?</a>
				<div id="FAQ-q2" class="collapsible-body text-muted" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1">
					<div class="top-margin1-xs">
						<p>
							Our current browser support philosophy recommends one version forward and two versions back with the exception of the SOE.
						</p>
						<p>
							The GUI uses progressive enhancement therefore older browsers may render interface elements less optimally however they must still
							support the following:
						</p>
						<ul class="lists">
							<li>Enable the user to complete a task</li>
							<li>Meet standard usability guidelines</li>
							<li>
								Comply to WCAG2 AA accessibility guidelines
								<p>This position takes into consideration:</p>
								<ul class="lists">
									<li>
										Weighing up the ROI of tweaking for older browsers whose usage is declining not growing, for small enhancements which add no
										additional value to the experience or completion of a task e.g. rounded corners etc.
									</li>
									<li>Simplifying code by minimising styling with anything other than CSS</li>
									<li>Less dependancy on visual designers to provide graphic assets and support</li>
									<li>More efficient workflow when building interfaces intended for multi-brand</li>
									<li>Future proofing the quality of graphics when displayed on high definition screens</li>
								</ul>
							</li>
						</ul>
						<p>
							Interface rending concerns in older browsers can be raised to CX but ultimately the AFS Digital Brand Director will decide if the brand
							presentation is acceptable or if an alternative must be explored
						</p>
					</div>
				</div>
			</li>
			<li>
				<a href="#FAQ-q3" class="js-collapsible">Who is responsible for bug fixing and testing?</a>
				<div id="FAQ-q3" class="collapsible-body text-muted" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1">
					<div class="top-margin1-xs">
						When you download an instance of the GUI and use it in your project you are responsible for testing and bug fixes. If you notice any bugs with the
						GUI please do let us know and we&rsquo;ll fix it up. Even better... send in a fix. We&rsquo;d be very grateful.
					</div>
				</div>
			</li>
			<li>
				<a href="#FAQ-q4" class="js-collapsible">If we use the GUI do we still need UX and UI designers?</a>
				<div id="FAQ-q4" class="collapsible-body text-muted" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1">
					<div class="top-margin1-xs">
						Yes. Every project no matter how small should have a UX designer and a UI designer. This will ensure that the interaction design and interface
						designs are consistent.
					</div>
				</div>
			</li>
			<li>
				<a href="#FAQ-q5" class="js-collapsible">Can I change theme.css?</a>
				<div id="FAQ-q5" class="collapsible-body text-muted" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1">
					<div class="top-margin1-xs">
						We do not recommend changing theme.css. To alter or add classes in your project please use an override css file.
					</div>
				</div>
			</li>
			<li>
				<a href="#FAQ-q6" class="js-collapsible">Can we use our own JavaScript library?</a>
				<div id="FAQ-q6" class="collapsible-body text-muted" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1">
					<div class="top-margin1-xs">
						Yes you can use your own JavaScript library however you are responsible for its implementation.</div></div>
			</li>
			<li>
				<a href="#FAQ-q7" class="js-collapsible">Is the GUI accessible?</a>
				<div id="FAQ-q7" class="collapsible-body text-muted" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1">
					<div class="top-margin1-xs">
						Yes as of version 1.0.0. the GUI complies to AA accessibility standards. We have been through a formal accessibility review to meet this
						requirement.
					</div>
				</div>
			</li>
			<li>
				<a href="#FAQ-q8" class="js-collapsible">How often will you do a release?</a>
				<div id="FAQ-q8" class="collapsible-body text-muted" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1">
					<div class="top-margin1-xs">
						As this project is in its infancy we are currently doing approximately 1 release per week. Releases will slow down as the GUI becomes more
						robust and established.
					</div>
				</div>
			</li>
			<li>
				<a href="#FAQ-q9" class="js-collapsible">Do we have to use the updated release?</a>
				<div id="FAQ-q9" class="collapsible-body text-muted" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1">
					<div class="top-margin1-xs">
						No you do not have to use the updated release. Every release will come with a change log. If you feel the new release could add value to your
						project then you can use it.
					</div>
				</div>
			</li>
			<li>
				<a href="#FAQ-10" class="js-collapsible">What frameworks are used to create in the GUI?</a>
				<div id="FAQ-q10" class="collapsible-body text-muted" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1">
					<div class="top-margin1-xs">
						The GUI is based on the Bootstrap framework version 3.x. Details can be found on the
						<a href="http://getbootstrap.com" target="_blank">bootstrap website.</a> Developers should be familiar with the Bootstrap framework in order
						to use the GUI correctly.
					</div>
				</div>
			</li>
			<li>
				<a href="#FAQ-11" class="js-collapsible">Can we receive a release note with the detail of each change? </a>
				<div id="FAQ-q11" class="collapsible-body text-muted" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1">
					<div class="top-margin1-xs">
						We have the GUI in source control, but we only make the HTML changes available in the change log. Each release is announced through BaseCamp
						for the moment.
					</div>
				</div>
			</li>
			<li>
				<a href="#FAQ-12" class="js-collapsible">How do we obtain an unminified version of the theme.css? </a>
				<div id="FAQ-q12" class="collapsible-body text-muted" aria-hidden="true" tabindex="-1">
					<div class="top-margin1-xs">
						Unminified versions are supplied as a download with each brand.
					</div>
				</div>
			</li>
		</ul>
	</div>
